00:17:32,400 --> 00:17:36,500
called Y Combinator led by Paul Graham

00:17:36,600 --> 00:17:39,500
He's like, "hey, I have this idea for a web site"

00:17:39,700 --> 00:17:42,200
and Paul Graham likes him enough and

00:17:42,300 --> 00:17:46,400
so yeah, sure, so Aaron drops out of school to this apartment

00:17:46,600 --> 00:17:48,900
So this used to be Aaron apartment when he lived here

00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:55,00
my big memories of my father telling me how difficult it was to get a lease

00:17:55,600 --> 00:17:58,400
cause Aaron had no credit and dropped out of college

00:17:58,700 --> 00:18:00,600
Aaron lived in what[?] called the living room

00:18:00,700 --> 00:18:04,000
and some of the posters here are left over from when Aaron lived here

00:18:04,200 --> 00:18:08,800
and the library, there were[?] more books then, but a lot of them are Aaron's

00:18:11,500 --> 00:18:17,400
Aaron YCombinator site is called "infogami" a tool to build websites

00:18:17,800 --> 00:18:19,700
but infogami struggles to find users

00:18:19,800 --> 00:18:24,600
and Swartz eventually merges his company with another Y Combinator project in need of help

00:18:24,800 --> 00:18:29,700
it was a project led by Steve Huffman and Alexis Ohanian called "reddit"

00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:33,900
Now we were starting from almost nothing, no users, no money, no code

00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:36,800
and growing day by day into hugely popular website

00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:38,800
and it shows no sign of letting up

00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:43,600
first we had a thousand users, than 10.000, then 20.000 and on and on, it's just incredible

00:18:44,200 --> 00:18:49,000
reddit becomes huge and it's a real sort of geeky corner of the Internet

00:18:51,700 --> 00:18:57,100
There's a lot of humor, there's a lot of art

00:18:57,300 --> 00:19:01,100
and there's just people who flocked to the site

00:19:01,300 --> 00:19:07,500
and made that site the main site they go to every morning to get their news.

00:19:07,600 --> 00:19:15,500
"reddit" kind of just borders on chaos at some level, so on the one hand its a place for people to discuss

00:19:15,600 --> 00:19:21,800
...news of the day, technology, politics and issues and yet there is a lot of kind of not safe for work

00:19:21,900 --> 00:19:29,800
...material, offensive material. Some subreddits were "trolls", "find a welcome home"

00:19:29,900 --> 00:19:33,800
and so in that sense reddit has been home to controversies as well

00:19:33,900 --> 00:19:36,700
It's kind of sits on the edge of chaos. 

00:19:36,900 --> 00:19:40,800
reddit catches the attention of the corporate magazine giant "Condé Nast"

00:19:40,700 --> 00:19:42,400
...who makes an offer to buy the company. 

00:19:42,600 --> 00:19:43,700
Some large amount of money,

00:19:43,900 --> 00:19:46,800
large enough that my dad was getting bugged with questions about like

00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:51,300
"How do I... store this money?"

00:19:51,400 --> 00:19:52,500
Like a lot of money

00:19:52,600 --> 00:19:53,800
Like a lot of money

00:19:53,900 --> 00:20:00,200
Like... probably more than a million dollars. But I don't actually know.

00:20:00,200 --> 00:20:01,800
And he's how old then?

00:20:02,100 --> 00:20:03,200
Nineteen or twenty?

00:20:05,100 --> 00:20:13,500
So he was in this apartment, they are like sat around on [?] couch hacking on "reddit" and...

00:20:13,600 --> 00:20:18,300
when they sold reddit they threw giant party and then all flew out to California

00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:20,300
the next day they left the keys with me.

00:20:23,700 --> 00:20:28,800
It was funny you know, he just sold a startup so we all kind of presumed he was the richest person around...

00:20:28,900 --> 00:20:34,100
but he.. ah.. he said "Oh, no. I'll take this tiny little shoe box sized room, that's all I need"

00:20:34,200 --> 00:20:42,500
...like he was barely larger than a closet. The idea of him spending his money on fancy objects just seems so implausible. 

00:20:42,700 --> 00:20:44,900
He explains it like, I like living in apartments,

00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:47,900
so I'm not gonna spend lot of money on a new place to live, I'm not gonna buy a mansion

00:20:47,900 --> 00:20:54,500
... and I like wearning jeans and t-shirt, so I am not gonna spend any more money on clothes. So like, it's really no big deal."

00:20:54,600 --> 00:21:00,500
What is a big deal to Swartz is how traffic flows on the Internet and what commands our attention?

00:21:00,600 --> 00:21:04,800
In the old system of broadcasting you're fundamentally limited by the amount of space in the airwaves.

00:21:04,900 --> 00:21:09,500
You know, you could always send out 10 channels over the airwaves for televisions right away

00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:13,200
even with cables you have 500 channels. On the Internet everybody can have a channel.

00:21:13,300 --> 00:21:17,800
Everyone can get a blog or a myspace page. Everyone has a way of expressing themselves. 

00:21:17,900 --> 00:21:19,800
And so what you see now is not a question of 

00:21:19,900 --> 00:21:24,800
"who gets access to the airwaves?". It's the question of "who gets control over the ways you find people?"

00:21:24,900 --> 00:21:29,500
You know you started seeing power centralizing in sites like Google, these sort of gate keepers< that tell you

00:21:29,500 --> 00:21:34,500
where on the internet where you want to go. The people who provides you, your sources of news information.

00:21:34,600 --> 00:21:39,500
So it's not you know, only certain people have a license to speak now everyone has a license to speak

00:21:39,500 --> 00:21:41,300
It's a question of "who gets heard?"

00:21:44,400 --> 00:21:49,700
After he started working, in San Fransico at Condé Nast, he comes into the office

00:21:49,800 --> 00:21:55,500
and they want to give him a computer with all this crap installed on it and say that he can't

00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:59,400
install any new things on this computer, which to a developer is outrageous, right?

00:21:59,500 --> 00:22:01,800
From the first day he was complaining about all this sutff.

00:22:05,600 --> 00:22:10,800
Gray wall, gray desks, gray noise. The first day I showed up here, I simply couldn't take it.

00:22:10,900 --> 00:22:14,800
By lunch time I had literally locked myself in a bathroom stall and started crying.

00:22:14,900 --> 00:22:19,600
I can't imagine staying sane with someone buzzing in my ear all day, let alone getting

00:22:19,700 --> 00:22:24,400
any actual work done. Nobody else seems to get work done either. Everybody's

00:22:24,500 --> 00:22:27,800
is always coming into our room to hang out and chat or invite us to play the new

00:22:27,900 --> 00:22:30,500
video game system that wired is testing.

00:22:32,700 --> 00:22:39,600
He really had different aspirations, that were politically oriented and Silicon valley

00:22:39,700 --> 00:22:46,600
just doesn't really quite have that culture that orients technical activity for the purposes

00:22:46,700 --> 00:22:50,200
of political goals. Aaron hated working for a corporation. They all hated

00:22:50,300 --> 00:22:53,100
working for Condé Nast but Aaron is like the only one who is not going to take it.

00:22:53,300 --> 00:22:57,800
And then basically he got himself fired by not showing up to work ever.

